Fundraising

October 2024 Crypto Fundraising Report

Sunny Shi

Nov 5, 2024 ⋅  16 min read

Key Insights

  • October 2024 saw a 96% month-over-month increase in deal volume to $1.76 billion, marking the highest level since November 2023. Deal count rose 25% to 282.
  • Early-stage deal volume grew 18% MoM to approximately $396 million, with notable investments across gaming, decentralized privacy, rollups, and perp DEXs, including Azra Games’ $42.7 million Series A, led by Pantera Capital.
  • The services sector led with $567 million raised, largely as a result of Praxis’s outsized $525 million financing. It was followed by the financial sector at $259 million, which included Kraken’s $100 million token grant from Optimism, and infrastructure at $92 million which included DePIN protocols’ Glow and GEODNET.
  • Animoca Brands led deal activity with nine investments, diversifying into sectors such as developer tooling, AI, and scalability solutions, signaling a shift from their traditional gaming focus.

In October 2024, deal volume increased ~96% MoM to $1.76 billion, marking the highest level since November 2023. Deal count increased ~25% MoM to 282. Notably, the month featured two substantial debt raises by mining companies Blockstream and Marathon Digital, collectively amounting to $410 million. When excluding mining operation raises from the analysis, deal volume increased ~51% MoM. The services sector led the month in deal volume, raising $567 million primarily due to a $525 million raise by Praxis. The financial sector came in second, raising $259 million, followed by the infrastructure sector, which raised $92 million, excluding the two mining operation financings.

Early Stage Deals

Early-stage deal volume grew ~18% MoM to ~$396 million. Early-stage deal count increased ~13% MoM to 72. Notable deals covered a wide range of categories, including gaming, decentralized privacy, rollups, and perp DEXs.

Azra Games

Azra Games raised a $42.7 million Series A led by Pantera Capital with participation from a16z and NFX. Azra Games, founded in 2022 by industry veteran Mark Otero, specializes in developing next-generation mobile role-playing games (RPGs) that emphasize immersive storytelling, dynamic combat, and engaging gameplay. Otero is renowned for his work on "Star Wars: Galaxy of Heroes," a top-grossing mobile game that has generated nearly $1 billion in revenue. The capital is earmarked for accelerating the development of their flagship project, currently code-named "Project Legends," which aims to deliver console-quality RPG experiences on mobile platforms.

Market Overview

Mobile is the most popular platform for gaming in 2024, leading Console and PC in both revenue and users with $93 billion in projected 2024 revenue and 2.8 billion users globally. Mobile devices have evolved to accommodate AAA standard games, and many publishers, including Take Two Interactive, EA, Activision Blizzard, and Ubisoft, have found success building flagship mobile titles. The mobile gaming format is particularly popular in Asia. Project Legends will look to compete and tap into this expansive market by offering a true next-generation AAA mobile experience.

Analysis

It is currently unclear how the game will incorporate GameFi elements into its offering, but given the crypto native funds on the cap table, it is likely that it will have some blockchain integrations. Play-to-earn crypto games like Off the Grid have largely been shifting towards building a premier gaming title first and figuring out in-game blockchain economies second. Azra Games’ leadership team has a wealth of experience building profitable Web2 mobile games, which bodes well for Project Legends’ success. Investors like Pantera and a16z will likely be more active in exploring how to flesh out the crypto mechanics of the title. While this endeavor certainly looks promising, AAA game development cycles are lengthy and expensive, and GameFi as a sector has thus far not found meaningful traction.

Citrea

Citrea raised a $14 million Series A led by Peter Thiel’s Founders Fund with participation from angel investors such as Erik Voorhees and Balaji Srinivasan. Citrea is a pioneering blockchain project that enhances Bitcoin's capabilities by integrating zero-knowledge (Zk) technology, transforming it from a passive store of value into an active, programmable asset. The platform utilizes Bitcoin as both a data availability and settlement layer, employing a BitVM-based trust-minimized two-way peg system known as "Clementine." This approach enables the creation of Bitcoin tokens on its blockchain, facilitating the development of decentralized applications (dApps) and expanding Bitcoin's utility beyond its traditional functions. Once mainnet is live, Citrea aims to support a Bitcoin layer that is fully EVM compatible.

Market Overview

Bitcoin programmability has been an increasingly popular narrative, with over forty total projects announced to date. In Q3 of 2024, TVL on rollups and sidechains reached an all-time high of over $1.4 billion, surging 20% QoQ. Rollups allow Bitcoin to evolve into a programmable smart contract network without altering the base layer. The area has been a growing source of fundraising with the recent surge in demand from the growth in Ordinals, Runes, and DeFi on Bitcoin.

Analysis

The debate around whether Bitcoin needs layer-2s is ongoing. While there seems to be some organic demand, Bitcoin’s conservative approach to upgrades, limitations as a smart contract platform, and security-first mentality limit the chain’s utility as a base layer. Furthermore, it is unclear whether Bitcoin natives will even express a desire to engage with programmability. However, given BTC’s substantial user base and economic value, the Bitcoin network offers perhaps the largest addressable market in crypto for an emerging programmable smart contract network. Citrea will have to deal with a multitude of competitors both within the Bitcoin landscape and elsewhere to win onchain activity.

For more insights into Bitcoin Rollups, check out Messari’s discussion piece titled Does Bitcoin need Layer-2s?

Financial Sector

Deal volume in the financial sector decreased ~2% MoM to $259 million. Deal count grew 23% MoM to 92. Exchanges represented 8 of the top 10 raises.

Kraken

It was revealed this month that crypto exchange Kraken had received a previously undisclosed grant from the Optimism Foundation of 25 million tokens, worth ~$100 million at the time and ~$42.5 million at current prices. The grant aims to support Kraken’s upcoming plans to develop "Ink," a new Layer 2 blockchain network built on Optimism's OP Stack framework and comes with a milestone-based unlock structure to align incentives.

Market Overview

Kraken and Coinbase are competing US-based centralized exchanges (CEXs) that have now both begun development on layer-2 networks to onboard their CEX users onchain. Coinbase’s Base and Kraken’s Ink also represent a growing interest to participate in OP’s Superchain, which has seen other big-name sign-ons from Sony and Uniswap. The OP Superchain plans to create an ecosystem of interoperable rollups on Ethereum.

Analysis

Base has been a major growth vertical for Coinbase and its success may have prompted Kraken to also pursue its own layer-2 built on Ethereum. By promoting onramps to Base and investing its sizable balance sheet into the Base ecosystem, Coinbase is future proofing its business. Base has helped Coinbase grow its wallet adoption, move further up the onchain stack, and monetize its sequencer. Kraken may look to replicate Coinbase’s strategy, however, it has a longer and tougher road ahead. Ink comes at a time of vulnerability for the Ethereum roadmap, and there are growing concerns around whether Layer-2s are becoming “value extractive”. Base’s centralized sequencer and economic ties to Coinbase have been sources of criticism for proponents of an aligned Ethereum ecosystem, and Kraken may find itself facing similar scrutiny.

Yellow Card

Yellow Card, a leading African cryptocurrency exchange, secured $33 million in a Series C funding round led by Blockchain Capital, and included Polychain Capital and Galaxy Ventures. Established in 2019, Yellow Card operates in 20 African countries, providing individuals and businesses with secure and cost-effective methods to buy and sell stablecoins such as USDT, USDC, and PYUSD using local currencies.

Market Overview

An emerging area of product-market-fit for crypto has been allowing those in underserved economies such as Africa and Latin America to access stablecoins. Africa's cryptocurrency market is experiencing rapid growth, driven by factors such as high inflation rates, currency devaluation, and limited access to traditional banking services. African users are leveraging digital assets to hedge against local currency volatility and facilitate cheaper cross-border transactions, with the majority of that activity involving stablecoins. Nigeria leads Africa in crypto and stablecoin usage, with its cryptocurrency market forecasted to generate $33 million in annual revenue after the country recently lifted its general ban on crypto. Local fintech startups like Yellow Card, Bitmama, BoundlessPay, and Afriex are building out stablecoin-based remittances, with Yellow Card being the leader in the space, having already facilitated over $3 billion in transactions across the African continent.

Analysis

As a licensed crypto on/off ramp in Africa, Yellow Card is positioned well to capture a portion of Africa’s growing amount of stablecoin transactions. The fund injection will help improve Yellow Card’s API and widget products which allow for greater international participation from businesses like Coinbase and expand the crypto offering for African users. Centralized crypto exchanges and payment platforms are high-moat businesses that benefit from first mover advantages, making it hard for upstart competitors to take share. On the other hand, Yellow Card’s business may face volatility if restrictions on stablecoin payments in the region tighten.

Infrastructure Sector

Deal volume in the infrastructure sector increased ~73% MoM to $92 million. Deal count decreased ~8% MoM to 24. Notable rounds include two raises from leading DePIN players.

Glow

Glow raised $30 million led by Framework and Union Square Ventures with participation from Lattice Ventures, Hack VC and Alliance DAO. Glow is a DePIN network focused on incentivizing the development of new solar farms that generate high-additionality carbon credits, using its native GLW token to reward solar operators for verified carbon reductions. Funds from the recent raise will go towards scaling their solar grids in India, which is expected to replace the energy consumption of 34,000 homes.

Market Overview

The carbon credit market is projected to grow significantly, with estimates suggesting it could reach $30 billion to $100 billion annually by 2030. Traditional carbon credit systems face challenges such as lack of global coordination, market fragmentation, and issues with transparency and verification. Glow aims to overcome these obstacles by leveraging blockchain's inherent transparency and security, providing a scalable solution for generating and verifying high-quality carbon credits. By focusing on solar energy, which has become the world's cheapest source of clean electricity, Glow addresses a substantial portion of global CO₂ emissions attributed to electricity generation.

Analysis

As demand for reliable carbon credits rises, Glow's transparent and efficient system could become a preferred solution for organizations seeking to offset their carbon footprints. Unlike most DePIN projects, Glow faces constraints on the supply-side rather than the demand-side. New funding will help unlock its growing supply of solar farms which will continue to generate revenue for the protocol. As validation for the Glow thesis, Glow has now become the highest earning DePIN protocol. Despite its promising outlook, the success of its token-based incentive system depends on the sustained value of GLW tokens in the face of consistent miner selling pressure. Additionally, ensuring the integrity of its auditing processes is crucial to maintain the credibility of its carbon credits, a hurdle which has been hard to overcome in the carbon credit markets today.

For more insights into Glow, check out Messari’s report on DePIN’s Glow Up.

GEODNET

GEODNET, a DePIN protocol providing real-time kinematics (RTK) data for hyper-precise GPS corrections, partnered with Animoca Brands to expand its presence in blockchain-enabled applications. GEODNET’s decentralized network of base stations corrects GPS data errors from 10–20 feet down to 1 cm accuracy, supporting use cases across agriculture, autonomous vehicles, AR, and drones. As part of the partnership, Animoca will directly invest in GEODNET and look to deepen its relationship with Mocaverse by leveraging better proof-of-location for Mocaverse’s consumer experiences.

Market Overview

The RTK data market is forecasted to reach $4.6 billion by 2030, driven by demand for high-precision location data in industries increasingly reliant on automation and real-time data. GEODNET’s DePIN model reduces the deployment cost of RTK correction networks by over 90%, giving it a significant competitive edge. Leveraging DePIN, GEODNET has scaled its network to over 10,000 nodes globally which we highlight could grow to 20,000 nodes by 2026, providing near-global coverage with significant cost reductions compared to traditional RTK models. GEODNET competes with centralized players in the RTK space which includes publicly traded companies like Trimble, Hexagon AB, Topcon and Fugro.

Analysis

GEODNET is positioned attractively as one of the only pure play RTK networks in both DePIN and Web2. Furthermore, location data works quite well within a DePIN framework given how hard and expensive it is to source accurate data through a centralized approach, particularly for difficult to access regions. As a first-mover, GEODNET can define a clear value proposition over centralized players. Outside of risks commonly associated with DePIN tokenomics, GEODNET’s biggest challenge will be fending off other competitors adopting a DePIN approach towards RTK data, given the low barriers of entry. Because GEODNET requires only a few RTK stations within each hex, new DePINs have a considerable opportunity to incentivize users who want to deploy additional stations in these areas. Additionally, DePINs often offer disproportionately higher rewards to early participants, enabling new networks to provide more attractive incentives than an established GEODNET.

For more insights into GEODNET, check out Messari’s report on DePIN for TradFi: A GEODNET Valuation and Breakdown

Services Sector

Deal volume in the services sector increased ~803% MoM to $567 million, primarily due to Praxis’ $525 million raise. Excluding Praxis, deal volume would have decreased ~34% to $41.5 million. Deal count for the sector decreased ~4% MoM to 22. Notable rounds outside of Praxis include two decentralized AI players, Sapien AI and Kiva AI.

Praxis

Praxis announced a $525 million financing, led by GEM Digital with a $500 million commitment. Other investors include Arch Lending, Manifold Trading, Tom Schmidt (GP at Dragonfly), Rob Hadick (GP at Dragonfly), and Max Novendstern (Co-Founder of World Network). Previously, Praxis had raised $19.2 million from investors like Paradigm, Robot Ventures, and Winklevoss Capital. Praxis, a Network State, is a global online community crowdfunding a physical city. GEM’s financing operates as a drawdown facility, where Praxis accesses funds incrementally as it achieves key development milestones. To tap into the capital, Praxis would need to first offer GEM tokenized interest in its real estate development, and then list those tokens on a publicly accessible exchange. Other milestones include securing government permits, land acquisition, and beginning construction.

Market Overview

Praxis is pioneering the novel Acceleration Zone sovereign model. Acceleration Zones are specialized economic areas designed to fast-track technological advancements by aligning them to national priorities, attracting skilled technologists and establishing frameworks that support innovation and reinvestment. In short, Praxis is building a next generation city which will act as an economic hub for innovators globally. The initial project aims to develop 1,000 acres of land and house 10,000 people. The project has already garnered attention, boasting over 14,000 community members globally, with plans to finalize a site in Latin America or the Mediterranean by Q1 2025.

Analysis

Praxis plans to use onchain infrastructure to handle essential societal functions like property management, currency, and contracts. It’s perhaps the most ambitious project being developed in crypto today. There have been previous attempts at this, most notably by CityDAO who had to forfeit operations after regulatory challenges, expenses, and team departures halted any meaningful progress, which all represent valid hurdles Praxis will have to overcome. A notable difference in Praxis’ roadmap is their plan to search for friendlier regulatory environments internationally, whereas CityDAO had largely looked to develop its community within the United States. Although CityDAO had its fair share of noteworthy supporters (including Mark Cuban and Vitalik Buterin), Praxis boasts a far more credible list of financial backers. Additionally, GEM’s financing is structured more as a tokenized real estate play, where their financial exit (if the commitments are realized) will likely be funded by aspirational “Praxians” or developers looking to own a piece of the future city.

Sapien AI and Kiva AI

Sapien AI raised $10.5 million in an extended seed round led by Variant with participation from Animoca Brands, Primitive Ventures and others. Kiva AI raised a $7 million pre-seed round led by Coinfund with participation from Hashkey Capital, NGC Ventures, and others. Both Sapien AI and Kiva AI address the growing demand for high-quality data labeling, a process crucial to the success of advanced AI models that require carefully refined data inputs to deliver accurate and reliable results. The two protocols leverage crypto incentives and onchain coordination to reward human labelors who contribute to the finetuning of AI models.

Market Overview

The data labeling and collection market is forecasted to reach $17.1 billion by 2030, expanding at a ~29% CAGR. Sapien has found early success sourcing demand with early customers including Alibaba, Baidu, TAL, and Midjourney. Its network spans 70 countries, and to date, the network has tagged over 2 million data points, with active labeler participation recently surpassing 10,000— growing at a 50% monthly rate. Kiva is earlier along its journey, but is led by founder Ahmed Rashad who recently helped grow Scale AI which employed over 1 million human labelors across 73+ countries within two years. The protocols compete with centralized labeling providers such as Appen, iMerit, Leap Steam, and LabelBox.

Analysis

Similar to GEODNET and RTK data collection, data labeling is a function in high demand that is more efficiently served by a decentralized onchain provider vs. a centralized institution. A decentralized data labeling network offers a streamlined global platform, allowing companies to overcome the friction of operating across various banking, legal, and labor systems. Token-based incentives further drive network growth, attracting skilled workers and improving data accuracy by offering rewards, on-chain reputation systems, and a share in the network’s potential success. By providing labeling without having to hire full-time labelors outright, these protocols can tap into niche and skilled labeling work for certain tasks without having to worry about employee utilization rates and maintaining consistent workloads. However, they will be competing against each other, and will need to find a way to attract and retain labelors who will likely be shopping across platforms for the best return on their time.

Investor Trends

Animoca Brands led other investors in deal activity, participating in nine rounds during the month. Notably, they made strategic investments across several verticals this month, including developer tooling, DeFi, AI, and scalability solutions, despite historically focusing on gaming-related investments. Investments in GEODNET help support partnerships that expand the capabilities of their own portfolio companies, while other investments (such as in Sapien AI, or Magma) may be genuine attempts to diversify as GameFi valuations momentarily trend down.

Conclusion

In October 2024, aggregate fundraising reached a new high for 2024, with deal volume up 96% MoM. Early stage volume saw modest growth, increasing 18% MoM, while a $525 million financing deal for Praxis drove much of the growth in later stage deal volume. October saw continued investor interest in DePIN, AI, Bitcoin programmability, and exchanges. Animoca was the most active investor by deal count, taking a noteworthy interest in protocols outside of gaming.
